{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17489728","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17489728"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T04:27:49+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T04:27:49+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"728"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"728","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/728"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.12,0.13,0.07,0.44,0.24]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"728"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"87533"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"728","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/728"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"728"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"71750"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"88"},{"type":"tags","id":"3343"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2404"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2721"},{"type":"contributions","id":"5897"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13771"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14968"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19120"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30056"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"87533","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/87533"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 64-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department four days after an elective right knee replacement. He has become confused and agitated. He is normally in good health and does not take any regular medications. He has a 25 pack-year smoking history and drinks four cans of beer daily. Standard prophylactic measures were taken for venous thromboembolism post-operatively.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell. His pulse rate is 100/min, blood pressure 115/75 mmHg, respiratory rate 20/min, SpO2 93% on room air, and temperature 37.4\u00b0C. The rest of the physical examination is unremarkable, apart from some reduced breath sounds at the right base.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHis pre-operative observations were normal.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next investigation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Blood alcohol concentration","Urine microscopy and culture","Blood cultures","Chest X-ray","CT pulmonary angiogram"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with post-operative confusion, agitation, and hypoxaemia, which requires prompt investigation to rule out serious complications. While several factors could contribute to his condition, the most appropriate next step is to perform a \u003Cstrong\u003Echest X-ray\u003C/strong\u003E. A chest X-ray is a quick, easily accessible, and non-invasive test that can help identify potential causes of hypoxaemia and confusion, such as pneumonia or pulmonary oedema. It\u0027s an important first-line investigation in this scenario, especially given the patient\u0027s smoking history and post-operative state.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECT pulmonary angiogram\u003C/strong\u003E is an important consideration given the post-operative state and risk of pulmonary embolism. However, it involves radiation exposure and contrast administration. It would be more appropriate to start with a chest X-ray and consider CTPA if the chest X-ray is normal or inconclusive and suspicion for PE remains high.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlood alcohol concentration\u003C/strong\u003E might be considered given the patient\u0027s history of alcohol consumption, but it\u0027s less likely to be immediately relevant given the post-operative setting and the presence of hypoxaemia. Alcohol withdrawal is a possibility, but other causes need to be ruled out first.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUrine microscopy and culture\u003C/strong\u003E would be appropriate if there were signs of a urinary tract infection, but there are no urinary symptoms mentioned in this case. While UTIs can cause confusion in older adults, it\u0027s not the most pressing concern given the patient\u0027s hypoxaemia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlood cultures\u003C/strong\u003E are important in evaluating for sepsis, but they wouldn\u0027t be the first-line investigation in this scenario. If the chest X-ray shows signs of infection or if the patient\u0027s condition worsens, blood cultures would then be appropriate.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn summary, while all these investigations may eventually be warranted, a chest X-ray is the most appropriate next step. It can quickly provide valuable information about potential causes of the patient\u0027s confusion and hypoxaemia, guiding further management decisions. If the chest X-ray is normal or inconclusive, further investigations including those listed in the other options may then be considered based on the clinical picture.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Post-operative agitation/delirium warrants a complete work-up to rule out infection/sepsis.","A patient who is hypoxaemic can become confused and agitated.","Chest X-ray is an appropriate first-line investigation for post-operative patients with new-onset confusion and hypoxaemia."],"references":["Moyle S. Postoperative Delirium. Melbourne (VIC): Ausmed [Online]; 2020. Available at: [https://www.ausmed.com.au/cpd/articles/postoperative-delirium].","Robinson TN, Eiseman B. Postoperative delirium in the elderly: diagnosis and management. Clin Interv Aging. 2008;3(2):351-355. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC2546478/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"71750"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"728"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"71750","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/71750"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-02-28T09:46:29+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-02-28T09:47:31+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"728"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"87533"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"65","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/65"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Investigations","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"typ